AB  - This paper examines a model of trade between a rich North and a poor South to consider the implications of the income inelasticity of demand for Southern goods and international demonstration effects for international economic development. Defining uneven development to mean a sustained increase in the ratio of Northern to Southern capital, the possibility and the conditions for its occurrence for these reasons, and its relation to the deterioration of the Southern terms of trade are examined.
